The Foundations of Web Development
Web development is built upon three main components, often called the "3 Musketeers":
HTML: Responsible for the structure of the web page.1
CSS: Used for styling the page.2
JavaScript (JS): Handles the logic and functionality.3
Connectivity: The <style> tag is used to connect HTML with CSS, while the <script> tag connects HTML with JavaScript.4

The Window Object and DOM
Window Object: This is a global object representing an open browser window. It is automatically created by the browser and 
contains various properties and methods.5
Document Object Model (DOM): When a web page loads, the browser creates a DOM of the page. It represents the structure of 
the document as a tree of objects, including elements like <html>, <head>, <body>, and various content tags like <div>, 
<h1>, and <img>.67
DOM Manipulation
DOM manipulation allows developers to dynamically change the content, structure, and style of a webpage using JavaScript.

1. Selecting Elements
Elements can be selected from the DOM using various methods:
By ID: document.getElementById(“myId”).8
By Class: document.getElementsByClassName("myClass").9
By Tag Name: document.getElementsByTagName(“p”).10

Query Selectors:
document.querySelector() returns the first element matching a specified CSS selector (ID, class, or tag).11
document.querySelectorAll() returns a NodeList of all matching elements.12

2. Properties
Once an element is selected, its properties can be accessed or modified:
tagName: Returns the tag name for element nodes.13
innerText: Returns or sets the text content of an element and all its children.14
innerHTML: Returns or sets the plain text or HTML content within an element.15
textContent: Returns textual content, including content from hidden elements.16

3. Attributes and Styles
Attributes: Use getAttribute(attr) to retrieve an attribute's value and setAttribute(attr, value) to change it.
Style: The node.style property allows for direct manipulation of an element's CSS.

4. Modifying the DOM Tree
Create: document.createElement("div") creates a new element.
Insert:
node.append(el): Adds the element at the end, inside the node.
node.prepend(el): Adds the element at the start, inside the node.
node.before(el): Adds the element before the node, outside of it.
node.after(el): Adds the element after the node, outside of it.
Delete: node.remove() deletes the specified node from the DOM.

Definition of an Event: An event is defined as a change in the state of an object. Events are triggered to notify the code 
about "interesting changes" that might impact how the code executes.

Types of Events:
Mouse Events: Examples include click and double-click.3
Keyboard Events: These include keypress, keyup, and keydown.4
Form Events: An example provided is the submit event.5
Print Events: Other event types such as print events also exist.6
Event Handling: This is the process of handling an event using the syntax node.event = () => { //handle here }. For instance,
a button click can be handled using btn.onclick = () => { console.log("btn was clicked"); }.78
Event Object: This is a special object containing details about the event. All event handlers can access its properties and 
methods, such as e.target, e.type, e.clientX, and e.clientY.910

Event Listeners: These are used to manage events with specific methods:
node.addEventListener(event, callback) is used to listen for an event.
node.removeEventListener(event, callback) is used to remove a listener.
To successfully remove a listener, the callback reference used must be the same as the one used when it was added

JavaScript Objects and Prototypes
Definition: A JavaScript object is an entity that possesses both state (properties) and behavior (methods).
Prototypes: Every JS object has a special property known as a prototype.
Setting Prototypes: You can set a prototype using __proto__.

Method Precedence: If an object and its prototype share the same method, the version defined in the object will be used.4
Classes in JavaScript

Purpose: A class acts as a program-code template used for creating objects.
Structure: Objects created from a class contain state represented by variables and behavior represented by functions.

The Constructor:
It is a special method that is automatically invoked by the new keyword.
Its primary role is to initialize the object.
Instantiation: An object is created from a class using the syntax: let myObj = new MyClass();

Inheritance and the super Keyword
Inheritance: This process involves passing down methods and properties from a parent class to a child class using the extends 
keyword.

Method Overriding: If both the parent and child classes have the same method, the child’s method is used instead.
super Keyword:
It is used to call the constructor of the parent class.
It allows a child class to access the properties and methods of its parent (e.g., super(args) or super.parentMethod(args)).

Error Handling
Try-Catch: This structure is used to handle potential errors in code without stopping the entire program.
Mechanism: The "normal code" is placed within the try block. If an error occurs, the catch (err) block is triggered to handle
it

Synchronous vs. Asynchronous Programming:
Synchronous: Code runs in a strict sequence where each instruction waits for the previous one to finish. This can sometimes
block the flow and cause delays in the UI.

Asynchronous: This execution style allows subsequent instructions to run immediately without blocking the program's flow.

Callbacks and Callback Hell:
A callback is a function passed as an argument to another function.
Callback Hell (or the Pyramid of Doom) occurs when nested callbacks are stacked, making the code difficult to manage and 
understand.

Promises:
A Promise is a JavaScript object representing the eventual completion of a task and serves as a solution to callback hell.
Promises have three states: Pending (undefined result), Resolved/Fulfilled (result is a value), and Rejected (result is an
error object).

They use .then() to handle successful results and .catch() to handle errors.

Async-Await:
An async function is a function that always returns a promise.
The await keyword pauses the execution of the surrounding function until a promise is settled.

IIFE (Immediately Invoked Function Expression):
An IIFE is a function that is executed immediately as soon as it is defined.
It can be written using standard function syntax or arrow functions, and it is often used with async blocks

